---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="RollyRush"
  description="A physics-based marble runner where you tilt, dodge and boost your way through increasingly chaotic obstacle courses. Built in Godot."
  engine="Godot"
  status="In Development"
  itch="#"
  tags={['Godot', 'GDScript', 'Physics', 'Mobile', 'Casual']}
>

  <!-- DEFAULT SLOT: ABOUT -->
  <h2>About the Project</h2>
  <p>
    RollyRush is a physics-based marble runner designed for mobile. You control a ball rolling
    through obstacle courses — tilting, boosting, and dodging your way to the finish line
    before the timer runs out.
  </p>
  <p>
    The game is designed around short, punchy sessions with escalating difficulty. Each level
    introduces a new mechanic — moving platforms, gravity flips, bounce pads — keeping the
    experience fresh without overwhelming the player.
  </p>

  <h3>Features</h3>
  <p>
    Tight physics-based controls, procedurally assembled level sections, a boost mechanic
    with risk/reward tradeoffs, and a clean mobile-first UI. Designed to be instantly
    understandable but hard to master.
  </p>

  <!-- TECH SLOT -->
  <Fragment slot="tech">
    <p>
      Built in Godot using GDScript. The physics are driven by Godot's built-in
      RigidBody3D system with custom impulse handling for the boost mechanic and tilt
      controls. Levels are assembled from modular sections at runtime to keep things
      varied without requiring hand-crafted layouts for every stage.
    </p>
    <p>
      The UI is built entirely in Godot's Control nodes with a custom theme to keep
      the mobile layout clean and touch-friendly.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- LEARNED SLOT -->
  <Fragment slot="learned">
    <p>
      Designing for mobile first is a different discipline. Every UI element needs to
      be thumb-reachable, every interaction needs to feel good with a tap, and
      performance constraints are tighter than on desktop. Godot's export pipeline
      made iteration fast, but profiling on device revealed a few surprises.
    </p>
    <p>
      The biggest lesson was in game feel — getting a physics ball to feel responsive
      and controllable while still behaving realistically required a lot of tweaking
      of mass, damping, and impulse values. Small changes have a huge impact on how
      fun the game feels.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

</ProjectLayout>
